#chapter_four
@chapter |number 4| |title Conclusion|

@section |title What was argued|

Three claims, in order. First: attention is labour, in something
close to @arendt_labour's sense — it must be done again the next
day. Second: looking is asymmetric, after @berger_looking. Third:
attending to something is a moral practice, after
@weil_attention, because it requires the suspension of the self.

@section |title What this implies|

It implies that the moral life is not chiefly a matter of choice
between actions; it is a matter of what one has paid attention to
long enough to be changed by. The agent who has not looked is
not, in any robust sense, a moral agent at all.

